HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 978
By McKenzie
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Diane Jordan of Knox
County.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Diane Jordan of Knox County; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Jordan was a trailblazing figure in local politics and always
recognizable by the statement hats she wore; she was a devoted public servant who worked
assiduously to improve the quality of life for her fellow citizens in numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, Diane Jordan, who was seventy-eight years old when she passed, was the
first Black woman to serve on the Knox County Commission; her tenure spanned from 1994 to
2007, during which time she was a Democrat representing District 6; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Jordan first ran for office with the intention of shining a light on police
brutality, which she said permeated her predominantly Black district; after her first term, she told
a local news outlet, "that has dropped off considerably since now it's out in the open."
During her second term as a Knox County commissioner, she shifted her focus to economic
development; and
WHEREAS, her public and private industry careers were expansive; after her political
career came to a close, she continued to serve her community in various capacities, including
as a member of the Beck Cultural Center's Board of Directors, Drug Free America, and the
Knoxville NAACP. She also served on the Knox County Election Commission; and
WHEREAS, a graduate of Austin-East Magnet High School, Mrs. Jordan worked in
reservations for Delta Airlines for twenty years; she obtained her real estate license in the 1990s
and was one of the few women in Knox County to hold an auctioneer's license; and
HJR0978
013614
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Mrs. Jordan was often duly lauded for the positive impact she had on Knox
County; she was the recipient of the YWCA's 1990 Tribute to Women Award for volunteer
service, and in 2017, the Interstate 275 bridge over Elm Street/Bernard Avenue was renamed
"Diane Jordan Pass" in her honor; and
WHEREAS, in addition to her important work throughout the community, Mrs. Jordan
was known for her extensive hat collection that included more than 125 cowboy hats and over
250 Sunday hats, which she donned as First Lady of her church; and
WHEREAS, a beloved family matriarch, Diane Jordan is survived by her husband of
forty-one years, Reverend John Jordan; eight children; and more than twenty grandchildren;
and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Jordan's life stands as a powerful testament to service, excellence,
and perseverance; her legacy is woven into the fabric of her community and will endure for
generations to come; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should remember the
bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Diane Jordan, reflecting fondly upon her
impeccable character and her stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family and friends of Mrs. Jordan.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
